  "prompt": "How should you treat a bump on your eyeball?",
  "response": "If you notice a bump on your eyeball, it's important to address it carefully. Here are some steps you can follow:\n\n1. **Avoid Touching or Rubbing**: Do not touch or rub your eye to prevent further irritation or potential infection.\n\n2. **Assess Symptoms**: Identify any associated symptoms such as pain, redness, vision changes, discharge, or swelling. These could indicate a more serious condition.\n\n3. **Do Not Self-Medicate with Over-the-Counter Drops**: Avoid using over-the-counter eye drops unless specifically directed by a healthcare provider.\n\n4. **Cold Compress**: If there is no sign of infection, you might use a cold compress to reduce any swelling or discomfort.\n\n5. **Maintain Eye Hygiene**: Ensure your hands are clean before touching your face. You can maintain proper eye hygiene to avoid infections.\n\n6. **Avoid Contact Lenses**: If you wear contact lenses, stop using them until the bump resolves and you speak with a healthcare provider.\n\n7. **Consult an Eye Specialist**: If the bump persists, worsens, or if you experience significant discomfort, vision changes, or discharge, seek professional medical advice. An ophthalmologist or optometrist can provide a proper diagnosis and recommend appropriate treatment.\n\nIt's important to err on the side of caution when dealing with eye issues. Professional guidance is essential to prevent complications.",
